            "body": "<p>You should make a json object put one parameter that key of parameter is \"credentials\" and the value of parameter is a json array that is a json object in it.\nor create a class that has the credentials object as a property for the label to show in the json<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>{\n    \"credentials\": [{\n        \"name\":\"abc\",\n        \"password\":\"pass\"\n    }]\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Example:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class MyInterfaceList {\n    @JsonProperty(\"credentials\")\n    private List&lt;MyInterface&gt; list;\n\n    public List&lt;MyInterface&gt; getList() {\n        return list;\n    }\n\n    public void setList(List&lt;MyInterface&gt; list) {\n        this.list = list;\n    }\n}\n\nfinal List&lt;MyInterface&gt; lists = new ArrayList&lt;MyInterface&gt;(4);\nlists.add(new MyImpl(\"abc\", \"pass\"));\nMyInterfaceList listHolder = new MyInterfaceList();\nlistHolder.setList(lists);\nfinal String json = mapper.writeValueAsString(listHolder);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Object Writer\nThis is the preferable option. Use a configured ObjectWriter instance to generate the JSON. In particular, we are interested in the withRootName method:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>final List&lt;MyInterface&gt; lists = new ArrayList&lt;MyInterface&gt;(4);\nlists.add(new MyImpl(\"abc\", \"pass\"));\nfinal ObjectWriter writer = mapper.writer().withRootName(\"credentials\");\nfinal String json = writer.writeValueAsString(lists);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
